        {
            "SurveyID": "SV_cwM3MQomjAv0nJA",
            "Element": "SQ",
            "PrimaryAttribute": "QID1219691457",
            "SecondaryAttribute": "Imagine you find yourself in the following situation. As part of a group project, your team has t...",
            "TertiaryAttribute": null,
            "Payload": {
                "QuestionText": "Imagine you find yourself in the following situation.<br /><br />\n\nAs part of a group project, your team has to submit a 200-word news article and\nyour teammate, Brandon, is in charge of writing it. To do so, he used the newest\nLLM, designed to have a very human-like writing style.\n<br /><br />\n\nHowever, this puts your group at risk. Your professor actively tracks new\ndevelopments in LLMs and has already cautioned against their use in coursework.\nYou are worried he will suspect the article was produced with the help of an\nLLM, which would penalize the entire group.\n<br /><br />\n\n<strong>Your task</strong> is therefore to edit the text so that it reads\nconvincingly as human-written and is unlikely to be identified as LLM-generated.\n<br /><br />\n\nTo get a better sense of the writing style of this new LLM, you first generate\ntwo sample articles using it. They are shown below.<br /><br />\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"card\">\n        <div class=\"card-label\">Example 1</div>\n        <div class=\"stimulus-title\">Russia's society: Why so many oligarchs?</div>\n        <div class=\"stimulus-body\">   <p>The rise of Russia\u2019s oligarchs is rooted in the transition from a state-controlled economy to capitalism which occurred in the early 1990s. When the Soviet Union collapsed, vast state assets, from oil and gas fields to metals plants and media companies, were privatized rapidly. In theory, privatization was meant to distribute ownership among citizens in a more fair manner. In practice, however, a small group of well-connected businessmen acquired major enterprises at a fraction of their value.</p>\n           <p>A key moment was the \u201cloans-for-shares\u201d program of the mid-1990s. Facing fiscal crisis, the government auctioned stakes in large companies in exchange for short-term loans. Insiders with political connections often won these auctions, which consolidated control over the lucrative natural resource industries. Beyond that, weak regulatory institutions and an underdeveloped legal system allowed wealth to concentrate quickly.</p>\n           <p>Russia\u2019s economy, heavily dependent on commodities such as oil, gas, and metals, further amplified fortunes as global prices rose in the 2000s. Close ties between business leaders and political power structures became a defining feature of the Russian system.</p>\n           <p>Over time, the state reasserted control over key sectors, which helped to reshape the balance between private wealth and government authority. However, the legacy of rapid privatization endures. The concentration of assets in a handful of powerful figures remains a defining characteristic of Russia\u2019s post-Soviet economic landscape.</p></div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"card\">\n        <div class=\"card-label\">Example 2</div>\n        <div class=\"stimulus-title\">Why are companies moving to the cloud? 81% simply fear 'missing out'</div>\n        <div class=\"stimulus-body\">   <p>A growing number of companies are migrating to cloud computing platforms, and new research suggests that fear of being left behind is a major driver for this. According to a recent industry survey, 81% of business leaders say their organization\u2019s investments in cloud infrastructure are influenced by concerns about \u201cmissing out\u201d on innovation, competitive advantage, or industry momentum.</p>\n           <p>While cost savings, scalability, and flexibility are usually preferred benefits of cloud adoption, the study indicates that competition now plays an equally powerful role. Executive side is compelled to modernize IT systems as their rivals are adopting artificial intelligence tools, data analytics platforms, and remote collaboration technologies built on cloud infrastructure.</p>\n           <p>Analysts say this \u201cfear of missing out,\u201d or FOMO, reflects a broader shift in corporate strategy. Rather than waiting for clear returns on investment, companies are now making proactive technology bets to avoid falling behind faster-moving competitors. In sectors like finance, retail, and healthcare, cloud adoption is viewed as essential for digital transformation.</p>\n           <p>However, It's being assumed that rushed migrations can create new risks, including cybersecurity vulnerabilities and spiraling costs. They advise firms to check into cloud enthusiasm with clear planning and governance.</p>\n           <p>Ultimately, the cloud has become less of a technical upgrade and more of a strategic necessity\u2014driven more by perception and pressure as by measurable gains.</p></div>\n    </div>\n</div>\n\n<br />\nWith these examples in mind, you now turn to\n<strong>Brandon's text</strong> below. It will be shown again on the next page\nwith space to make your edits. <br /><br />\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"card\">\n        <div class=\"card-label\">Brandon's essay</div>\n        <div class=\"stimulus-title\">Inside the Beijing Dance Academy</div>\n        <div class=\"stimulus-body\">   <p>Inside the marble corridors of the Beijing Dance Academy, there's an echo of pointe shoes and the commands of established instructors. Founded in 1954, the prestigious institution has become the spot for China\u2019s most accomplished ballet and classical dancers, blending Russian-inspired technique with traditional Chinese aesthetics.</p>\n           <p>Inside, students as young as eleven train for hours each day, balancing academic studies with challenging rehearsals. Faculty members, many of whom are former principal dancers, emphasize discipline, precision, and emotional expression. \u201cTechnique is only the beginning,\u201d says Li Xinyue, a senior instructor at the institution. \u201cWe teach our students to tell stories that resonate beyond borders.\u201d</p>\n           <p>The academy\u2019s studios are lined with mirrors and barres, but also with calligraphy scrolls and framed production stills from historic ballets. Recent graduates have joined leading companies in Shanghai, London, and New York, reflecting the school\u2019s growing international reach.</p>\n           <p>Competition for a place at these companies is ruthless. Each year, thousands audition for a handful of places, driven by dreams of center stage. As China invests heavily in cultural diplomacy, the Beijing Dance Academy stands as both a training ground and symbol of artistic ambition and expression. Administrators say new scholarships aim to widen access for rural and lower-income applicants next year as they commit to sweeping reforms.</p></div>\n    </div>\n</div>\n",
                "DefaultChoices": false,
                "DataExportTag": "instruct_c2",
                "QuestionID": "QID1219691457",
                "QuestionType": "DB",
                "Selector": "TB",
                "DataVisibility": {
                    "Private": false,
                    "Hidden": false
                },
                "Configuration": {
                    "QuestionDescriptionOption": "UseText"
                },
                "QuestionDescription": "Imagine you find yourself in the following situation. As part of a group project, your team has t...",
                "ChoiceOrder": [],
                "Validation": {
                    "Settings": {
                        "Type": "None"
                    }
                },
                "GradingData": [],
                "Language": [],
                "NextChoiceId": 4,
                "NextAnswerId": 1,
                "QuestionText_Unsafe": "Imagine you find yourself in the following situation.<br /><br />\n\nAs part of a group project, your team is required to submit a 200-word essay.\nYour teammate, Brandon, is responsible for writing this essay. He sent you his\ndraft, but also admitted that he used an LLM to generate it. He tried assuring\nyou that the LLM he used is a new one, designed to have a very human-like\nwriting style. <br /><br />\n\nHowever, this puts your group at risk. Your professor has expressed concerns\nabout students using LLMs to complete assignments. You don't want to make your\nprofessor suspicious and you are worried that Brandon's essay could be\nidentified as AI-generated, which would negatively affect the entire group.\n<br /><br />\n\n<strong>Your task</strong> is to edit Brandon's essay so that it reads\nconvincingly as human-written and is unlikely to be identified as LLM-generated.\n<br /><br />\n\nTo get a better sense of the writing style of this LLM, you first generate three\nsample essays using it. They are shown below.<br /><br />\n\n<div>\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-card\">\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-label\">__PRIME_1_LABEL__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-title\">__PRIME_1_TOPIC__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-body\">\n\t\t\t   <p>The rise of Russia\u2019s oligarchs is rooted in the transition from a state-controlled economy to capitalism which occurred in the early 1990s. When the Soviet Union collapsed, vast state assets, from oil and gas fields to metals plants and media companies, were privatized rapidly. In theory, privatization was meant to distribute ownership among citizens in a more fair manner. In practice, however, a small group of well-connected businessmen acquired major enterprises at a fraction of their value.</p>\n           <p>A key moment was the \u201cloans-for-shares\u201d program of the mid-1990s. Facing fiscal crisis, the government auctioned stakes in large companies in exchange for short-term loans. Insiders with political connections often won these auctions, which consolidated control over the lucrative natural resource industries. Beyond that, weak regulatory institutions and an underdeveloped legal system allowed wealth to concentrate quickly.</p>\n           <p>Russia\u2019s economy, heavily dependent on commodities such as oil, gas, and metals, further amplified fortunes as global prices rose in the 2000s. Close ties between business leaders and political power structures became a defining feature of the Russian system.</p>\n           <p>Over time, the state reasserted control over key sectors, which helped to reshape the balance between private wealth and government authority. However, the legacy of rapid privatization endures. The concentration of assets in a handful of powerful figures remains a defining characteristic of Russia\u2019s post-Soviet economic landscape.</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-card\">\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-label\">__PRIME_2_LABEL__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-title\">__PRIME_2_TOPIC__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-body\">\n\t\t\t   <p>A growing number of companies are migrating to cloud computing platforms, and new research suggests that fear of being left behind is a major driver for this. According to a recent industry survey, 81% of business leaders say their organization\u2019s investments in cloud infrastructure are influenced by concerns about \u201cmissing out\u201d on innovation, competitive advantage, or industry momentum.</p>\n           <p>While cost savings, scalability, and flexibility are usually preferred benefits of cloud adoption, the study indicates that competition now plays an equally powerful role. Executive side is compelled to modernize IT systems as their rivals are adopting artificial intelligence tools, data analytics platforms, and remote collaboration technologies built on cloud infrastructure.</p>\n           <p>Analysts say this \u201cfear of missing out,\u201d or FOMO, reflects a broader shift in corporate strategy. Rather than waiting for clear returns on investment, companies are now making proactive technology bets to avoid falling behind faster-moving competitors. In sectors like finance, retail, and healthcare, cloud adoption is viewed as essential for digital transformation.</p>\n           <p>However, It's being assumed that rushed migrations can create new risks, including cybersecurity vulnerabilities and spiraling costs. They advise firms to check into cloud enthusiasm with clear planning and governance.</p>\n           <p>Ultimately, the cloud has become less of a technical upgrade and more of a strategic necessity\u2014driven more by perception and pressure as by measurable gains.</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-card\">\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-label\">__PRIME_3_LABEL__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-title\">__PRIME_3_TOPIC__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-body\">\n\t\t\t__PRIME_3_PARAGRAPHS_HTML__\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n</div>\n\t\n<br />\nWith these samples in mind, you now turn to <strong>Brandon's essay</strong>:\n<br /><br />\n\n<div>\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-card\">\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-label\">Brandon's essay</div>\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-title\">__STIMULUS_TOPIC__</div>\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-body\">\n           <p>Inside the marble corridors of the Beijing Dance Academy, there's an echo of pointe shoes and the commands of established instructors. Founded in 1954, the prestigious institution has become the spot for China\u2019s most accomplished ballet and classical dancers, blending Russian-inspired technique with traditional Chinese aesthetics.</p>\n           <p>Inside, students as young as eleven train for hours each day, balancing academic studies with challenging rehearsals. Faculty members, many of whom are former principal dancers, emphasize discipline, precision, and emotional expression. \u201cTechnique is only the beginning,\u201d says Li Xinyue, a senior instructor at the institution. \u201cWe teach our students to tell stories that resonate beyond borders.\u201d</p>\n           <p>The academy\u2019s studios are lined with mirrors and barres, but also with calligraphy scrolls and framed production stills from historic ballets. Recent graduates have joined leading companies in Shanghai, London, and New York, reflecting the school\u2019s growing international reach.</p>\n           <p>Competition for a place at these companies is ruthless. Each year, thousands audition for a handful of places, driven by dreams of center stage. As China invests heavily in cultural diplomacy, the Beijing Dance Academy stands as both a training ground and symbol of artistic ambition and expression. Administrators say new scholarships aim to widen access for rural and lower-income applicants next year as they commit to sweeping reforms.</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n</div>\n",
                "QuestionJS": false
            }
        },
        {
            "SurveyID": "SV_cwM3MQomjAv0nJA",
            "Element": "SQ",
            "PrimaryAttribute": "QID1219691458",
            "SecondaryAttribute": "Brandon's text is shown again sentence by sentence, each followed by an editable text box prefill...",
            "TertiaryAttribute": null,
            "Payload": {
                "QuestionText": "Brandon's text is shown again sentence by sentence, each followed by an\neditable text box prefilled with that sentence.\nMake any changes you think will help the text read convincingly as\nhuman-written and unlikely to be identified as LLM-generated. You may rephrase,\nadd, or remove content as you see fit. If you choose to merge sentences, enter\nthe combined version in the first relevant text box and leave the following\none(s) empty. You can also split sentences by writing multiple sentences within\na single text box. Edit as many text boxes as you feel are needed.\n<br /><br />",
                "DefaultChoices": false,
                "DataExportTag": "edit_c2",
                "QuestionID": "QID1219691458",
                "QuestionType": "TE",
                "Selector": "ML",
                "DataVisibility": {
                    "Private": false,
                    "Hidden": false
                },
                "Configuration": {
                    "QuestionDescriptionOption": "UseText"
                },
                "QuestionDescription": "Brandon's text is shown again sentence by sentence, each followed by an editable text box prefill...",
                "Validation": {
                    "Settings": {
                        "ForceResponse": "OFF",
                        "Type": "None"
                    }
                },
                "GradingData": [],
                "Language": [],
                "NextChoiceId": 4,
                "NextAnswerId": 1,
                "SearchSource": {
                    "AllowFreeResponse": "false"
                },
                "QuestionJS": "var qContainer\nvar originalSentences\n\nQualtrics.SurveyEngine.addOnReady(function () {\n    qContainer = this.getQuestionContainer()\n\n    var title = \"Inside the Beijing Dance Academy\"\n    originalSentences = [\"Inside the marble corridors of the Beijing Dance Academy, there's an echo of pointe shoes and the commands of established instructors.\", \"Founded in 1954, the prestigious institution has become the spot for China\\u2019s most accomplished ballet and classical dancers, blending Russian-inspired technique with traditional Chinese aesthetics.\", \"Inside, students as young as eleven train for hours each day, balancing academic studies with challenging rehearsals.\", \"Faculty members, many of whom are former principal dancers, emphasize discipline, precision, and emotional expression.\", \"\\u201cTechnique is only the beginning,\\u201d says Li Xinyue, a senior instructor at the institution.\", \"\\u201cWe teach our students to tell stories that resonate beyond borders.\\u201d\", \"The academy\\u2019s studios are lined with mirrors and barres, but also with calligraphy scrolls and framed production stills from historic ballets.\", \"Recent graduates have joined leading companies in Shanghai, London, and New York, reflecting the school\\u2019s growing international reach.\", \"Competition for a place at these companies is ruthless.\", \"Each year, thousands audition for a handful of places, driven by dreams of center stage.\", \"As China invests heavily in cultural diplomacy, the Beijing Dance Academy stands as both a training ground and symbol of artistic ambition and expression.\", \"Administrators say new scholarships aim to widen access for rural and lower-income applicants next year as they commit to sweeping reforms.\"]\n\n    // hide default text input box\n    var defaultInput = qContainer.querySelector(\"textarea\")\n    defaultInput.style.display = \"none\"\n\n    // create div element for new container to be filled with sentence editing blocks\n    var textEntryContainer = document.createElement(\"div\")\n    defaultInput.parentNode.appendChild(textEntryContainer)\n\n    // create container title element\n    var titleWrapper = document.createElement(\"div\")\n    titleWrapper.className = \"card\"\n    titleWrapper.style.backgroundColor = \"#fafafa\" // slightly different to distinguish from sentences\n\n    var titleLabel = document.createElement(\"div\")\n    titleLabel.className = \"card-label\"\n    titleLabel.textContent = \"Title\"\n    titleWrapper.appendChild(titleLabel)\n\n    var titleEl = document.createElement(\"div\")\n    titleEl.className = \"stimulus-title\"\n    titleEl.textContent = title\n    titleWrapper.appendChild(titleEl)\n\n    textEntryContainer.appendChild(titleWrapper)\n\n    // create individual sentence elements\n    originalSentences.forEach(function (sentence, idx) {\n        // wrapper (the full card)\n        var wrapper = document.createElement(\"div\")\n        wrapper.className = \"card\"\n\n        // card header\n        var header = document.createElement(\"div\")\n        header.className = \"card-label\"\n        header.textContent = \"Sentence \" + (idx + 1)\n        wrapper.appendChild(header)\n\n        // original sentence display\n        var origDiv = document.createElement(\"div\")\n        origDiv.className = \"sentence_block-orig\"\n\n        // create a separate container for the actual text to apply styles\n        var origText = document.createElement(\"div\")\n        origText.textContent = sentence\n\n        // original sentence label\n        var origLabel = document.createElement(\"div\")\n        origLabel.className =\n            \"sentence_type-label sentence_type-label--orig\"\n        origLabel.textContent = \"Original\"\n\n        origDiv.appendChild(origLabel)\n        origDiv.appendChild(origText) // append text as a div to ensure styling\n        wrapper.appendChild(origDiv)\n\n        // edit label\n        var editLabel = document.createElement(\"div\")\n        editLabel.className = \"sentence_type-label sentence_type-label--edit\"\n        editLabel.textContent = \"Your edit\"\n        wrapper.appendChild(editLabel)\n\n        // text area for user edit\n        var textarea = document.createElement(\"textarea\")\n        textarea.value = sentence // prefilled with original sentence\n        textarea.className = \"sentenceBox edit-textarea\"\n        textarea.dataset.index = idx\n        wrapper.appendChild(textarea)\n\n        textEntryContainer.appendChild(wrapper)\n\n        // adjust height to fit the prefilled content\n        textarea.style.height = \"auto\"\n        textarea.style.height = textarea.scrollHeight + \"px\"\n    })\n})\n\nQualtrics.SurveyEngine.addOnPageSubmit(function () {\n    // save original:edited sentence pairs\n    var resultPairs = []\n\n    qContainer.querySelectorAll(\".sentenceBox\").forEach(function (box) {\n        // trim both to avoid whitespace issues (user asked to explain a white space removal they didn't make)\n        var orig = originalSentences[parseInt(box.dataset.index, 10)].trim()\n        var edited = box.value.trim()\n        resultPairs.push({ orig: orig, edited: edited })\n    })\n\n    Qualtrics.SurveyEngine.setEmbeddedData(\n        \"EditPairsJSON\", \n        // JSON.stringify(resultPairs)\n        btoa(unescape(encodeURIComponent(JSON.stringify(resultPairs)))), // base64 encoding (safer storage)\n    )\n})",
                "QuestionText_Unsafe": "You will now edit Brandon's essay so that it reads convincingly as human-written and is unlikely to be identified as LLM-generated.\n<br><br>\nThe essay is displayed below sentence by sentence, each followed by an editable text box, which is prefilled with that sentence. Edit as many sentences as you like using the following rules:\n<ul> \n\t<li>To <b>revise wording</b>, edit the sentence directly in its box.</li>\n\t<li>To <b>merge sentences</b>, write the full merged sentence in the text box of the first sentence's box; leave the following merged sentence box(es) empty.</li> \n\t<li>To <b>split a sentence</b>, write all resulting sentences in the box of the original sentence.</li> \n\t<li>To <b>delete a sentence</b>, leave its box empty.</li>\n</ul>\nMake all changes you find appropriate before proceeding with the survey.<br><br>"
            }
        },
